{
  "roast_critique": "Wow, Emily, you’ve managed to cram an entire marketing textbook into a one‑page résumé. Opening with “Dynamic marketing professional” feels like you’re auditioning for a hype‑man role, and the phrase “up to 45%” in your summary is about as precise as a weather forecast. Your “Senior Marketing Manager” bullet points are stuffed with big numbers—$3.2 M revenue increase, 3.2× ROAS, 38% time cut—yet you completely forget to tell us *how* you did it, leaving the reader guessing if you just waved a magic wand. The older roles sound like you were busy “producing SEO‑optimized copy” and “coordinating trade shows” without any proof that those activities actually moved the needle. And “References: Available upon request” is the résumé equivalent of “I’m not lazy, I’m just delegating,” which is frankly the most over‑used line in the industry. Good luck standing out when hiring managers are already snoozing after the first paragraph.",
  "professional_suggestions": [
    "Trim the buzz‑filled summary to a concise 2‑3 sentence value proposition that showcases a unique impact, and replace vague qualifiers like “up to 45%” with concrete, verifiable results.",
    "Add specific metrics or outcomes for the earlier roles (e.g., percentage increase in qualified leads from trade shows) and briefly describe the tactics or tools you used to achieve them, ensuring consistency across all experience sections.",
    "Streamline the layout: remove the redundant “References available upon request,” consider adding a hyperlink to your LinkedIn profile, and ensure bullet formatting and punctuation are uniform for a cleaner, more professional appearance."
  ],
  "rating": 8
}

{
  "roast_critique": "Wow, Marcus, your resume reads like a DevOps brag‑fest written by a hype‑machine. You start with an \"Objective\" that is basically a copy‑paste of every senior SRE LinkedIn headline – \"Seasoned DevOps Engineer with 8 years of experience…\" – as if the hiring manager can’t tell the difference between “seasoned” and “still using buzzwords”. You sprinkle every paragraph with percentages and “‑‑” numbers (\"99.96 % uptime\", \"45 % reduction in MTTR\", \"cutting provisioning time from weeks to minutes\") but you never say *why* those matter to the business – are we talking about $ millions saved or just vanity metrics? The dreaded \"References available upon request\" at the very bottom feels like a relic from the 90s that only clutters the page. And while you’ve got a laundry list of tools, there’s no hint of soft‑skill prowess – no mention of team leadership, stakeholder communication, or conflict resolution, which are half the job when you’re “driving operational excellence”. In short, you’ve built an impressive tech checklist but forgot to turn it into a compelling story.",
  "professional_suggestions": [
    "Replace the generic Objective with a concise 2‑sentence summary that highlights a unique value proposition (e.g., specific business impact you delivered) and eliminates buzz‑word filler.",
    "For each quantified achievement, add a brief business context (cost savings, revenue impact, customer satisfaction) so recruiters can gauge real value, and trim any redundant metrics.",
    "Remove the outdated \"References available upon request\" line, and incorporate a short soft‑skill bullet (e.g., cross‑functional leadership, incident communication) to balance the heavy technical emphasis."
  ],
  "rating": 8
}

{
